      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Religious exemptions are a major, ongoing legal and ethical debate, and there is no single \"right\" way to handle them. Proponents argue that protecting religious freedom is a fundamental right, allowing individuals to practice their faith without government coercion. Conversely, critics argue that granting exemptions undermines the principle of equal protection under the law, particularly when it impacts vulnerable groups. The ideal balance, in theory, is to ensure religious liberty while simultaneously upholding universal civil rights.",
      "source": "target",
